\begin_layout Abstract
A notable example of a discontinuous-everywhere function that is not traditional
ly integrable, yet, when properly defined, can be integrated, is derivative
 of the Minkowski question mark function.
 It, and its generalizations are known as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

multi-fractal measures
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Some subject matter overlaps that of 
\begin_inset LatexCommand citet
key "Ve-L06"

\end_inset

.
 This paper includes numerical results for the Fourier transform of the
 measure.
 It also provides an exact result, expressing the measure as an infinite
 product of piece-wise continuous functions, specifically, as a product
 of Mobius transforms of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $(ax+b)/(cx+d)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

