\begin_layout Standard
Consider the integral 
\begin_inset Formula \[
b_{n}=\int_{0}^{1}\exp\left(2\pi inx\right)\frac{dx}{?^{\prime}\left(?^{-1}\left(x\right)\right)}\]

\end_inset

Because the denominator is discontinuous everywhere, the above is not well-defin
ed without additional work.
 Noting the denominator is in the form of a Jacobian, naively performing
 the change of variable 
\begin_inset Formula $u=?^{-1}(x)$
\end_inset

 leads to 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
b_{n}=\int_{0}^{1}\exp\left(2\pi in?\left(u\right)\right)du\label{eq:fourier coffs}\end{equation}

\end_inset

This last expression is easily evaluated by numerical means.
 By symmetry of the question-mark function, the coefficients are purely
 real.
 A graph of these coefficients are shown in figure 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Fourier-of-Jacobian"

\end_inset

.
 A fractal self-similarity is clearly evident.
\end_layout

