\begin_layout Standard
Numerical access to these coefficients begs a question: what would the inverse
 transform look like? Formally, the inverse is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\frac{1}{?^{\prime}\left(?^{-1}\left(x\right)\right)} & =\sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}b_{n}e^{-2\pi inx}\\
 & =b_{0}+2\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}b_{n}\cos\left(2\pi nx\right)\end{align*}

\end_inset

This function is, again, easily accessibly by numerical means; it is shown
 in figure 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:The-Jacobian"

\end_inset

.
 The structure shown in the figure is highly suggestive: it appears to be
 an arrangement of Dirac delta functions of varying strengths, located at
 the dyadic rationals.
 The structure is not entirely straight-forward, but a hypothesis for this
 distribution is presented in the next section.
\end_layout

