\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section takes a brief moment to justify the label of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Cantor set measure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 used in the paragraphs above.
 It proceeds by the definition of the canonical Cantor set, then a class
 of Cantor sets with non-zero measure, and finally, a class of generalized
 Cantor sets with arbitrary measures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The traditional Cantor set is constructed by considering first the closed
 unit interval, and then removing the open set that is the middle third:
 by removing the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1/3\,,\,2/3\right)$
\end_inset

.
 One then removes the middle thirds from the remaining two closed intervals,
 and then recursively proceeding 
\emph on
ad infinitum
\emph default
.
 It was Cantor's achievement to show that the remaining set is uncountable
\begin_inset LatexCommand cite
key "Can1884"

\end_inset

.
 This procedure can be performed multiplicatively; namely, by considering
 the function 
\begin_inset Formula \[
c\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
1 & \mbox{ for }0\le x\le\frac{1}{3}\\
0 & \mbox{ for }\frac{1}{3}<x<\frac{2}{3}\\
1 & \mbox{ for }\frac{2}{3}\le x\le1\end{cases}\]

\end_inset

The indicator function for the Cantor set is then given as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mu_{C}\left(x\right)=\prod_{k=0}^{\infty}\tilde{c}\left(3^{k}x\right)\label{eq:cant-set-meas}\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the tilde defined as before.
 This indicator function is equal to 1 for any point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 belonging to the Cantor set, and zero otherwise.
 A formal measure, defined in standard measure-theoretic terms, can be defined
 for this function.
 In plainer language, it is integrable: one finds that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
0=\int_{0}^{1}\mu_{C}\left(x\right)dx\]

\end_inset

that is, the measure of the Cantor set is zero.
 The principal difficulty of constructing the formal measure is the realization
 that the standard open-interval topology for real interval won't do.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The indicator function above can be generalized in a variety of ways; the
 most important generalization for the present purposes is to define a measure
 that is not vanishing on the unit interval.
 This may be done by considering an indicator function of the form 
\begin_inset Formula \[
c_{w}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
1 & \mbox{ for }0\le x\le w\\
0 & \mbox{ for }w<x<1-w\\
1 & \mbox{ for }1-w\le x\le1\end{cases}\]

\end_inset

indicating a pair of closed intervals of width 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

, which is then recursively compounded by the middle-thirds construction.
 But geometrically increasing the widths, so as not to get zero measure.
